🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. How do you stand out in a competitive market? This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture

🚀 Understanding the 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 (𝗦𝗥𝗣) in .NETMany developers unknowingly violate SRP by writing large classes that handle multiple responsibilities. This makes the code hard to maintain, test, and extend.🔴 The Problem ❌ The class handles 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗲𝘀 (data fetching, salary calculation, reporting). ❌ Any 𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗺𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗼𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝘀. ❌ The code is 𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆.✅ Applying SRP: The Right ApproachTo follow SRP, we split the responsibilities into separate classes. 🎯 Why This is Better? ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝗰𝗵 𝗰𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗿𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆. ✅ 𝗘𝗮𝘀𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗶𝗳𝘆. ✅ 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗳𝗲𝗮𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗮𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗰𝗼𝗱𝗲.🔥 Key TakeawayThe 𝗦𝗶𝗻𝗴𝗹𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗽𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲 ensures that each class 𝗱𝗼𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗲𝗹𝗹, making your code 𝗰𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗻, 𝗺𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘀𝗰𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲.👉 What are your thoughts on SRP? Let’s discuss in the comments! 👇hashtag#CSharp hashtag#DotNet hashtag#SOLIDPrinciples hashtag#SoftwareEngineering hashtag#SRP hashtag#CleanCode

Beyond the Job Description: The Talent You're Probably OverlookingFounders, here’s the truth: If you're only seeing what’s in someone’s job title…You’re missing out on their real value.In startups and lean teams, every hire matters.But here’s where we go wrong: We hire someone for marketing, ops, or admin—and forget to ask: 💡 What else can they do? 💡 What lights them up? 💡 What untapped skills are we not using?One of the best-kept secrets of high-functioning teams? They don't just hire talent—they discover it.Your project manager might be a brilliant UX thinker. Your content writer might have sharp product instincts. Your customer support rep could be a natural community builder.You don't need a bigger team. You need better visibility into the one you already have.✅ Here’s how to start uncovering hidden strengths:🔹 Ask beyond the role: “What do you love doing that we haven’t tapped into yet?" 🔹 Create low-risk test projects: Let them lead outside their lane—watch what happens. 🔹 Host internal talent showcases: Short, fun sessions where team members show off a skill or passion project. 🔹 Give permission to explore: Make it okay to step outside the box—creativity thrives when it's welcomed.Small teams don’t need more people—they need more possibility thinking.✨ When you unlock hidden strengths, you build loyalty, energy, and growth—without increasing headcount.💬 Founders & team leads: What’s one hidden talent you discovered on your team—and how did you tap into it?Let’s share ideas 👇 hashtag#Startups hashtag#TeamDevelopment hashtag#FoundersTips hashtag#UnlockPotential hashtag#PeopleStrategy hashtag#GrowthMindset hashtag#TalentOptimization

How do you stand out in a competitive market? The key piece of advice that I can give is to be proactive • reach out to your current contacts & look to expand your network• Connect with specialist recruiters in your area (we are here to help)• Track your applications and follow-up on processes • Reach out to Hiring Managers / Talent Partners on LinkedIn - express your interest in the role (this is controversial however it's better than having your resume lost under a pile of applications and worst case you make a new connection)•Tailor your resume - highlight relevant key skills, achievements, and responsibilities - ensure your resume is succinct and easy to read• Get active on LinkedIn - switch your status to 'open to work'. This will inform recruiters & talent partners that you're approachable and will increase the flow of incoming contact In a competitive market, you want to give yourself the best opportunity you can to stand out - It's important to remember that it may take some time and disappointment, however through proactivity and persistence you will secure a new role - trust the process! hashtag#trusttheprocess hashtag#dotnet hashtag#architecture
